    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "E.g.\r\n\r\n```\r\ncdef int foo(const int& i):\r\n  def bar():\r\n    return i\r\n  return bar()\r\n```\r\n\r\nproduces invalid assignment code when creating the closure. ",
    "closed_at": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "COLLABORATOR",
            "body": "I've hit this while trying to get https://github.com/cython/cython/pull/3323 working again with the most recent master (but may end up working around it there irrespective of this).\r\n\r\nIt seems like there are three options:\r\n* Capture by value (i.e. make a copy of `i` in the closure of `bar`) - this is the safest option.\r\n* Capture by \"fake reference\" (i.e. pointer really) - this breaks if the closure outlives whatever `i` is, but it is arguably doing what the user asked.\r\n* Disallow it in Cython and just raise an error there (instead of producing a bunch of invalid C++ code).",
